05642nam a22009615i 9780691224695DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2022056588  a97806912246957 a10.1515/97806912246952doi  a(DE-B1597)644552  a(OCoLC)1373237174  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBJ1520 4aBJ1520b.D68 2023 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a170223/eng/202303161 aDouglass, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMandeville’s Fable :bPride, Hypocrisy, and Sociability /cRobin Douglass. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tConventions -- tIntroduction -- tPart I Moral Psychology -- t1 Pride and Human Nature -- t2 The Morality of Pride -- t3 Sociability, Hypocrisy, and Virtue -- tPart II Historical Narratives -- t4 The Desire of Dominion and Origin of Society -- t5 Honour, Religion, and War -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy we should take Bernard Mandeville seriously as a philosopherBernard Mandeville’s The Fable of the Bees outraged its eighteenth-century audience by proclaiming that private vices lead to public prosperity. Today the work is best known as an early iteration of laissez-faire capitalism. In this book, Robin Douglass looks beyond the notoriety of Mandeville’s great work to reclaim its status as one of the most incisive philosophical studies of human nature and the origin of society in the Enlightenment era. Focusing on Mandeville’s moral, social, and political ideas, Douglass offers a revelatory account of why we should take Mandeville seriously as a philosopher.Douglass expertly reconstructs Mandeville’s theory of how self-centred individuals, who care for their reputation and social standing above all else, could live peacefully together in large societies. Pride and shame are the principal motives of human behaviour, on this account, with a large dose of hypocrisy and self-deception lying behind our moral practices. In his analysis, Douglass attends closely to the changes between different editions of the Fable; considers Mandeville’s arguments in light of objections and rival accounts from other eighteenth-century philosophers, including Shaftesbury, Hume, and Smith; and draws on more recent findings from social psychology.With this detailed and original reassessment of Mandeville’s philosophy, Douglass shows how The Fable of the Bees—by shining a light on the dark side of human nature—has the power to unsettle readers even today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConduct of lifevEarly works to 1800. 0aConduct of life-Early works to 1800. 0aConduct of life. 0aConsciencevEarly works to 1800. 0aConscience-Early works to 1800. 0aConscience. 0aEthicsvEarly works to 1800. 0aEthics-Early works to 1800. 0aEthics. 0aMandeville, Bernard,-1670-1733. 0aSociologyzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aSociology-Great Britain-History. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aBernard Mandeville.  aDavid Hume.  aShaftesbury.  aethics.  ahuman nature.  ahypocrisy.  amoral philosophy.  amoral psychology.  apassions.  apolitical philosophy.  apride.  arecognition.  ashame.  asociability.  avice.  avirtue.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook 